chitectural firms such as OMA, Reiser + Umemoto, and Foreign Office, as well as the art of Matthew Barney, Ai Weiwei, Sherrie Levine, and many others, After Art provides a compelling and original theory of art and architecture in the age of global networks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArt and society. 0aArtxPsychology. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAcropolis Museum.  aAi Weiwei.  aAlejandro Zaera-Polo.  aAlexander Nemerov.  aAndy Warhol.  aAntonio Negri.  aArt Basel.  aArt history.  aArt museum.  aArt world.  aArthur Danto.  aBernard Tschumi.  aBill Ayers.  aBoris Groys.  aBruno Latour.  aCalculation.  aCapitalism.  aClement Greenberg.  aCommodity.  aConceptual art.  aContemporary art.  aCreative Commons.  aCultural Property (Japan).  aCultural capital.  aCurator.  aCustomer.  aDamien Hirst.  aDe Stijl.  aDecolonization.  aDiagram.  aDigital photography.  aDissemination.  aElectronic Disturbance Theater.  aEmblem.  aEpistemology.  aFinancial capital.  aFrank Gehry.  aGlobalization.  aGuggenheim Museum Bilbao.  aHannah Arendt.  aHans Belting.  aHigh culture.  aIconology.  aIdeology.  aIllegal immigration.  aIncome.  aInfrastructure.  aInstance (computer science).  aInstitution.  aInstitutional Critique.  aKunsthalle Wien.  aLawrence Lessig.  aLe Corbusier.  aMIT Press.  aManifesto.  aMarket economy.  aMatthew Barney.  aMichael Hardt.  aMichel Foucault.  aModern architecture.  aModernism.  aMuseum.  aNarrative.  aNeoliberalism.  aNewspaper.  aOverproduction.  aOwnership.  aOxford University Press.  aParametricism.  aPhotography.  aPostcard.  aPublic sphere.  aPublication.  aRachel Harrison.  aRem Koolhaas.  aRepatriation (humans).  aRhetoric.  aRichard Meier.